      Eternal September
   =20
 =20
Here is a simplistic, wrong, but almost plausible history of stock-market i=
nvesting:=09Stock markets were invented to let people finance productive bu=
sinesses and share in the profits. You and 100 other people give a railroad=
 company some money to build tracks, it builds tracks, it runs trains, it m=
akes money, it pays you all a nice 7% dividend out of the money it makes.=
=09Markets quickly became a way for=C2=A0people to gamble on speculative ve=
ntures. You couldn=E2=80=99t get a ton of financial information about those=
 investments, so you were just guessing which ones were good. You bought st=
ocks because you thought other people would buy them. =E2=80=9CThe professi=
onal investor is forced to concern himself with the anticipation of impendi=
ng changes, in the news or in the atmosphere, of the kind by which experien=
ce shows that the mass psychology of the market is most influenced,=E2=80=
=9D  wrote Keynes in 1936. =E2=80=9CThe actual, private object of the most =
skilled investment today is =E2=80=98to beat the gun,=E2=80=99 as the Ameri=
cans so well express it, to outwit the crowd, and to pass the bad, or depre=
ciating, half-crown to the other fellow.=E2=80=9D If you wanted to analyze =
how much to pay for a stock, you would concern yourself with questions of=
=C2=A0mood. You would =E2=80=9Cread the tape,=E2=80=9D get a sense of how t=
he market=C2=A0felt, and then buy if you thought people were going to be bu=
llish and sell if you thought they=E2=80=99d be bearish. The profits of the=
 underlying business=C2=A0might=C2=A0affect the mood, but they were not you=
r primary concern. The mood was.=09But in 1934,  Benjamin Graham invented d=
iscounted cash flow analysis,[1] and stocks became (again) a way to bet on =
the future profits of productive enterprises. If you wanted to analyze a st=
ock, you=E2=80=99d analyze its operations and build a spreadsheet and predi=
ct its future financial results and do some math to those results to get a =
current value. If the value was higher than the price, you=E2=80=99d buy th=
e stock. There were reasons that this approach became dominant. The crash o=
f 1929 and the ensuing depression meant that the mood was=C2=A0bad, so inve=
sting in productive businesses was relatively more attractive than betting =
on mass enthusiasm. The creation of the modern US system of securities regu=
lation in the 1930s meant that stock manipulation was=C2=A0harder to do, wh=
ile getting financial information about companies was easier: You actually=
=C2=A0could=C2=A0analyze cash flows. But, also, doing math to sober busines=
s analyses just seems more=C2=A0professional. If investing is a game of mas=
s psychology and gambling, then it is not quite respectable=C2=A0to make yo=
ur living from it. If investing is a business of building complex quantitat=
ive models to allocate capital to its best uses, then it is much more reput=
able and impressive, and you can hire lots of Harvard applied-math majors t=
o do it.=09In roughly 2021 the pendulum swung back again. Now the way you i=
nvest in stocks is by guessing which stocks other people will want to buy, =
math and financial statements are worthless, and the reputable finance busi=
nesspeople keep getting blown up by online gamblers.And so now, if you want=
 to analyze the value of a stock, you will   ask questions like =E2=80=9Cwh=
en do college students come back to school and start gambling again?=E2=80=
=9DThe recent resurgence in retail-trading favorites won=E2=80=99t let up a=
nytime soon, says Jaime Rogozinski, founder of the popular chat forum WallS=
treetBets.=E2=80=9CSummer vacation is over, everyone is back in school and =
that=E2=80=99s when the activity gets to kick back up,=E2=80=9D Rogozinski =
said in an interview with Bloomberg Markets.The drivers are the same as the=
y were in January 2021: relatively distressed, highly shorted companies are=
 once again getting pushed higher by day trader enthusiasm. And the frenzy =
is likely to continue =E2=80=9Cas long as we don=E2=80=99t disable a buy bu=
tton,=E2=80=9D says Rogozinski, who no longer moderates the Reddit forum.=
=C2=A0On the other hand here=E2=80=99s a college student who  made the most=
 of his summer vacation:A 20-year-old university student has made a roughly=
 $110mn gain by selling a stake in struggling retailer Bed Bath & Beyond, a=
fter its stock price soared during a month of frenzied trading reminiscent =
of last year=E2=80=99s meme stock boom.Jake Freeman, an applied mathematics=
 and economics major at the University of Southern California, acquired nea=
rly 5mn shares in Bed Bath & Beyond in July, according to regulatory filing=
s, after dismal earnings and the ousting of its chief executive sent its st=
ock price plummeting.Freeman bought his stake at under $5.50 a share. On Tu=
esday, Bed Bath & Beyond surged to more than $27 a share. As the stock soar=
ed, Freeman sold more than $130mn worth of stock from his TD Ameritrade and=
 Interactive Brokers accounts.Freeman=E2=80=99s sale was well-timed. Shares=
 in Bed Bath & Beyond tumbled more than 20 per cent on Thursday after the i=
nvestor and meme-stock champion Ryan Cohen disclosed on Wednesday evening t=
hat he intended to sell his entire stake of almost 12 per cent in the compa=
ny.That=E2=80=99s from the Financial Times last Thursday; here is a follow-=
up about how Freeman tried to give Bed Bath & Beyond Inc. some  meme-y corp=
orate finance advice:The novel solution he proposed for Bed Bath involved u=
sing the high volatility in its stock price to offer bondholders a deal tha=
t would lighten its senior debt load from $1.2bn to $500mn. The plan hinged=
 on the company offering stock warrants and convertible notes to debt holde=
rs in exchange for reducing the company=E2=80=99s leverage. If the company =
repaired its balance sheet and the share price recovered, the warrants woul=
d go up in value.Here=E2=80=99s his  July letter to the company outlining t=
he proposal. In one sense it=E2=80=99s a fairly straightforward distressed =
debt restructuring idea: If you=E2=80=99re a company with bonds trading at =
20 to 40 cents on the dollar,[2] then you can try to buy those bonds back f=
or 30 to 50 cents=E2=80=99 worth of new bonds, giving=C2=A0you=C2=A0less de=
bt and your bondholders a nice profit. In another sense, it is a complicate=
d way to say =E2=80=9Clook, you are a meme stock, which means that investor=
s want to YOLO your call options, so what you should do is create some call=
 options and sell them to pay off your debt.=E2=80=9D Warrants and converti=
bles are company-issued call options, and call options are the meme-iest wa=
y to trade meme stocks.Really the corporate-finance advice that you=E2=80=
=99d=C2=A0like=C2=A0to give to a meme-stock issuer is: Every Monday, if you=
r stock is trading at $10, sell a bunch of warrants with a $20 strike price=
 expiring on Friday, for say $1 each.=C2=A0If your stock doubles, you sold =
stock at $20, which is a lot better than you expected. If, much more likely=
, your stock doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0double, then you=E2=80=99ve made a free $=
1, every week. People want to overpay to gamble on your stock =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0they are buying short-dated listed call options anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0so=
 you might as well let them overpay you. In practice this is tricky: It=C2=
=A0seems weird to do=C2=A0one-week=C2=A0warrants, and anyway a warrant isn=
=E2=80=99t quite the same thing as a weekly listed call option.=C2=A0(In fa=
ct warrants on meme-y stocks seem much=C2=A0less=C2=A0attractive to retail =
investors than the underlying stock.[3]) Still, the basic advice of =E2=80=
=9Cyou are a meme stock so you ought to be selling options to gamblers=E2=
=80=9D feels correct.Notice, though, that Bed Bath & Beyond ignored his adv=
ice and the stock soared for  purely meme reasons:In August, Bed Bath share=
s started soaring following renewed momentum on Reddit, where moderators of=
 the WallStreetBets channel had lifted a ban on discussing the stock. It ca=
talysed a furious rally in Bed Bath shares that Freeman said caught him off=
 guard. =E2=80=9C[People] were really hyping it up on WallStreetBets, which=
 just led to more and more fear of missing out,=E2=80=9D he said.At the sta=
rt of last week, the shares climbed higher still after Ryan Cohen, the chai=
r of GameStop and a meme stock figurehead, filed documents with the SEC on =
Monday detailing a previous=C2=A0purchase in February and March of a large =
number of call options in Bed Bath =E2=80=94 derivatives that can deliver a=
 windfall if a stock rises in value.It=E2=80=99s not cleverly harnessing me=
me-stock volatility to clean up the balance sheet. It=E2=80=99s message boa=
rds and misreading=C2=A0the actions of =E2=80=9Ca meme stock figurehead.=E2=
=80=9D It=E2=80=99s mass psychology, not corporate finance. In a sense, if =
you buy a big chunk of a meme stock and give the company advice on how to d=
o meme corporate finance, you are doing the right thing. (Meme-stock activi=
sts =E2=80=9Ccan nudge companies to be dumber so their stocks will go up,=
=E2=80=9D   I once wrote.) In another sense, if you buy a meme stock and th=
ink about corporate finance at all, you are making a mistake.In other meme-=
stock news, I entirely missed   the rise and fall of AMTD Digital Inc. this=
 summer, which I feel pretty good about. At its peak it was worth $470 bill=
ion, and not because of cash flows.
