      Equifax insider trading
   =20
 =20
In July 2017, credit reporting company Equifax Inc. was hacked, disclosing =
=E2=80=9Cpersonally identifiable information of millions of consumers.=E2=
=80=9D In September 2017, Equifax publicly disclosed the hack, and its stoc=
k fell 14%. In between those events, Equifax apparently went around telling=
 lots of people about the hack without disclosing it publicly, and all of t=
hem insider traded? I mean,   not really all of them. But it is striking   =
how many  insider trading cases came out of that hack. One model here is th=
at Equifax mobilized an unusual number of people to look into the hack, man=
y of them were not seasoned financial professionals, and so a lot of them i=
nsider traded in dumb obvious ways that got them caught. Another model is t=
hat insider trading on a data breach is somehow more offensive=C2=A0than in=
sider trading on, say, a merger, so the Securities and Exchange Commission =
put more effort into catching insider traders=C2=A0than it usually does.Any=
way here=E2=80=99s a good one from last week:The SEC's complaint, filed in =
the Northern District of Georgia, states that Equifax engaged a Chicago-bas=
ed public relations firm in August 2017 to assist with handling the inquiri=
es expected to be generated by the announcement of the intrusion and breach=
. According to the complaint, Ann M. Dishinger, who worked as a finance man=
ager at the public relations firm, learned about the Equifax breach through=
 her position and tipped her significant other, Lawrence M. Palmer (L. Palm=
er), with the nonpublic news. The SEC alleges that L. Palmer then contacted=
 a former business client and arranged for the client to purchase out-of-th=
e-money Equifax put options in the client's brokerage account with the unde=
rstanding that the client and L. Palmer would split any trading profits obt=
ained.The guy was the romantic partner of finance manager at a public relat=
ions firm hired by Equifax=E2=80=99s outside counsel, which is pretty far r=
emoved from the source of the information; if he knew about the hack and tr=
aded on it, think about how many other people did. And Palmer was allegedly=
 unsophisticated enough  that he had to ask =E2=80=9Ca former business asso=
ciate=E2=80=9D of his =E2=80=9Cfor advice on how to purchase options that w=
ould take advantage of what he thought would be bad news for the company.=
=E2=80=9D The associate recommended put options and apparently gave Palmer =
a brief options tutorial, and then Palmer allegedly =E2=80=9Casked his form=
er business associate to purchase $1,000 in Equifax put options in his brok=
erage account, claiming that he himself did not have a brokerage account an=
d suggesting that the circumstances were so urgent that he did not have tim=
e to open his own account.=E2=80=9DThe associate bought the options, and th=
en this allegedly happened:L. Palmer later reimbursed his former business a=
ssociate for $1,000 of the funds used to purchase the put options. In the m=
emo section of the check, L. Palmer wrote the words =E2=80=9CBlue Horseshoe=
.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CBlue Horseshoe=E2=80=9D was an apparent reference to Mic=
hael Douglas=E2=80=99s instruction to Charlie Sheen in the 1987 movie=C2=A0=
Wall Street=C2=A0to use a coded message to convey inside information, namel=
y, =E2=80=9C[y]ou tell the man that Blue Horseshoe loves Anacott Steel.=E2=
=80=9DWhat!? I promise, the SEC has seen =E2=80=9CWall Street.=E2=80=9D You=
